climbs.name: TUMS (Toss Up My Shoes)
climbs.fa: Idk, probably a spider or something

content.description:
Sit start with right hand sidecling and left on undercling block. Bump left up the arete then find a way to get to the top. Funnest way is just throwing right hand from the start hold. Somewhere between LCC V4 and Joe's V5/6 (I'll give you V9 if you don't dab the tree branch on the top out). Walk off the back and all the way around from Death Spike (have someone toss up your approach shoes) or just jump off onto a pad.

If anyone has info on this, let me know and I'll change it
content.location: 5 seconds uphill and on the left side of the trail from the Big Hug Prow boulder. Sit start on right hand sidecling and left hand on an underling jug block

content.description: The epitome of Little Rock spraywall-ness. Start on the V4 arete Left to Right, then iron cross out to Grand Gallery/High on Crack and top out as per that problem. Stay off the slab behind you after transitioning into High on Crack

content.description: If you like your holds small and sharp, this is the line for you (you sick masochistic freak)! Start on the right side of the Brian boulder, right hand on a side pull crimp and left hand side pull jug in the crack. Hit the jug meat hook then traverse left through the face on some small crimps. Big move to the jug at the lip then top out on High On Crack
content.location: Right side of the Brian Boulder

content.description: Start sitting on lowest chalked up sloper on the arete. Follow the arete with you hands until the top of the boulder. Feet are pretty good the entire way. (Heel hook on the arete helps a lot at the beginning)
content.location: boulder #1

content.description: This is essentially an alternate start to dig deep right; but it changes the climb completely! Lay down start with left hand on what is the right hand start for dig deep (golf ball looking pinch) and right hand in the neat yet painful double pocket feature. Go into dig deep right. The taller you are the easier the top is and harder the bottom; the shorter you are the easier the bottom is and harder the top is. Depending on your beta, this thing can have some pretty cool movement.
content.location: On the right side of the dig deep boulder.

content.description: start at the left of the face. right hand on pocket, left hand on crimp
content.location: bouler #3

climbs.name: Grand Gallery Arete (aka High on Crack)

content.description:
AKA: High on Crack

Start with your left hand on a crimp and right hand in a good dish-looking sloper. Follow the arete of the boulder and top out where the block has broken off. What was a jug to top out on is now a V1 sequence on good slopers. Some say a heel-hook helps in the middle, others say it does not. Play around with the beta and send it!
content.protection: At least two boulder pads to protect the top-out
content.location:
Boulder #3

Problem #1

content.description:
Stand start on big vertical edge next to orange streak. Lunge to 2 small positive pockets. Go left to jutting black point, and mantle up to large pocket.

Downclimb: go way right up under the Pine Tree. Keep going right until you can walk off.
content.location:
loc: 40.28637,-111.62836

Satellite View

10-15 minutes to big bolted boulder in riverbed; From here, continue up the dry riverbed 200 yards further (6-7 more minutes) up around bend. Small cliff joins riverbed on left. Problems sit on small hill on left side.

content.description: After hitting a polished right hand crimp, sink a high heel-toe cam and come onto a left hand sloper. Crux is getting out of this position up to the lip.
content.location: This boulder is most easily accessed from the upper trail on Imperial Way. Follow the trail up to the Big Hug boulder with the prow hanging over the middle of the wash, then continue up wash about 30-60 seconds, scrambling over some slippery, river-polished rock. On the right, you'll see a boulder with a prominent roof feature. Finnicky starts matched on a ledge to the right of the chock block in the middle of the boulder and climbs out the roof on the right.

content.description: To the left of Fire and Ice.  Starts with right hand in undercling pocket, left hand up to deep pocket, dynamic/static move (depending on height) up to a right hand pinch, bump right up to sloper jug to an easy top out.
content.location: about 200 yards up from the main bouldering area. Just to the left of Fire and Ice on short cliff band.

content.description: Right exit of Dig Deep. Same low start on a left hand side pull and right hand crimp block. Find a way to make a hard move out the dirt to a jug pocket, then either make easier, smaller moves up bad slopers to the jug or throw left up to a bad sloper 6 inches to the left of the jug and then make a desperate move to get your right hand to the jug. Feet up and the jug makes the top out easy. The first move on this problem seems to be harder if you're taller
content.protection: 2-3 pads or 1 and a spotter to move it
content.location:
Park atÂ Little Rock Canyon Trail,

3974 N Sherwood Dr, Provo, UT 84604. Follow the trail up to the wash and follow the riverbed up until you see the boulder on your left.

content.description:
A hard traverse on bad crimps and tricky feet that doesn't let up until you hit the jugs. Make sure you know your top out beta!

Variation:

For a harder line, staying off the left hand pinch/crimp before the move into the pocket makes the climb feel solid V9.
content.protection: 3 pads: 1 to span the gap between boulders on the right of the climb, 1 for the start, 1 for the boulder behind. Make sure your pad won't slide out if you fall or you'll break your butt!
content.location: On the Brian Boulder, same start as Spocker Shocker but move right and finish on 3.5 Pounds Off My Back. Listed as the project in the beta photo.
